The reason of one-hot encoding for labels is that, our model, as the number of neurons of last layer suggests, estimates the probability of belonging to each of classes for any input; Therefore we need to encode the (true) labels in one-hot way, so we prepare the proper inputs for our loss function that we choose for the model which is _categorical_crossentropy. Also in general, one-hot encoding is useful and suggested when there is on order between values of categorical clolumn.

The above table is a summary of our model. we have two hidden layers. In Param column we can see the number of parameters for each layer that must be trained. As we understood in previous project (project5-part1) the weight matrix for each layer was in shape of #_layer_inputsize #_layer_outputsize. Also each layer had bais vector of size #_layer_outputsize. So the total parameters to be trained is equal to (#_layer_inputsize + 1) #_layer_outputsize.

In the table above, in first layer for instance we must have : (10000 + 1) * 2048 = 20482048 parameters which we have. For other layers is the same thing.

3-1) Optimizer impact¶

Momentum is some kind of moving average which would denoise the data and bring it closer to the original function. This average is called exponentially weighed average.

With Stochastic Gradient Descent we dont compute the exact derivate of our loss function. Instead, were estimating it on a small batch. Which means were not always going in the optimal direction, because our derivatives are noisy. So, exponentially weighed averages can provide us a better estimate which is closer to the actual derivate than our noisy calculations. This is one reason why momentum might work better than classic SGD.

The other reason lies in ravines. Ravine is an area, where the surface curves much more steeply in one dimension than in another. Ravines are common near local minimas in deep learning and SGD has troubles navigating them. SGD will tend to oscillate across the narrow ravine since the negative gradient will point down one of the steep sides rather than along the ravine towards the optimum. Momentum helps accelerate gradients in the right direction

If we look at metrics measures table in evaluation part of two senarios(momentum = 0.5 or 0.9), we can see that we get a better result when we use mmentum = 0.9. In this case, we have higher average f1 and accuracy in both tarin and validation data

Increasing momentum hyperparameter, doesn't always help to get better results. When you are increasing moemntum, you average over larger number of examples, since momentum is kind of moving exponentially weighted average. So training will be slow; Also averaging from large number of previous gradients may not be suitable, because that much history of gradients Participating in calculating current gradient is not necessary.

3-2) Epochs impact¶

Generally whenever we want to optimize, we use gradient descent. Gradient descent has a parameter called learning rate. In one iteration alone we can not guarantee that the gradient descent algorithm would converge to a local minima with the specified learning rate. That is the reason why we use multiple epochs and iterate again for the gradient descent to converge better.

Usually in problems that we need a iterative approaches and algorithms to solve the problem and get optimal solution, we may need to multiple epochs.

Using too much epochs, may cause the model, become train-data-specific or in ohther word, it may cause overfitting in model. So too many epochs in not good, To avoid this, we can use tril and error method to find suitable number of epochs or we can use EarlyStopping callback mechanism of tf.keras. This function is passed to fit method of model, when training, and aviod continuting training when overfitting is happening. This is exactly what we have used in above section to evoid overfitting and as you can see, we end up to a better macro avg f1 for validation data which is 76%

In the obove, we trained a model with loss of MSE, and as shown in metrics measure table, the macro avg f1 is lower than when we used _categorical_crossenctropy

The choice of cost function is tightly coupled with the choice of output unit. The choice of how to represent the output then determines the form of the loss function.

In Multi-Class Classification Problems such as our problem, the problem is framed as predicting the likelihood of an example belonging to each class. as we chose last layer to have 4 neurons with softmax activation function, each outputs probabily of belongining to a specific class. So _categorical_crossentropy loss is suitable because this function is used to measure loss and cost between two probabilty distributions.

Where MSE is mostly used in Regression Problems. In this case, output layer has one node with linear activation function, outputing predicted real value.

visited_indexes = []

while(count < 10):
  random_ind = np.random.randint(0, len(test_data.classes), 1)[0]
  if(y_test_pred[random_ind] != y_test_true[random_ind] or random_ind in visited_indexes):
    continue
  visited_indexes.append(random_ind)
  plt.subplot(2,5, count+1)
  img = PilImg.open('dataset/test/'+test_data.filenames[random_ind])
  img.thumbnail(TARGET_SIZE)
  plt.imshow(img)
  plt.title('y_true: ' + code_to_label_m[y_test_true[random_ind]] + ', y_pred: ' + code_to_label_m[y_test_pred[random_ind]])
  count += 1

Falsely predicted pictures:

The reason of such a misprediction may be that the background of mispredicted picture is mostly used in false-predicted class. For example the second picture of first row is look like a background of a elk picture.

Also we can see that raven and bald_eagle pictures are commonly misclassified interchangeably, which is kind of reasonable.
